display="inline"><![CDATA[a=q_{2}r_{1}+r_{2}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r_{1}=q_{3}r_{2}+r_{3}]]></fr:tex>, …, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r_{n+1}=q_{n+3}r_{n+2}]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r_{n+2}=\gcd (a,b)]]></fr:tex> since:</fr:p>
<fr:p>(1) <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(r_{n+2})\subseteq (a,b)]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
<fr:p>(2) <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(a,b)\subseteq (r_{n+2})]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
<fr:p>Hence by (1) and (2) and since <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-001P.xml"
addr="ra-001P"
title="Euclidean Domains are Principal Ideal Domains">Euclidean Domains are Principal Ideal Domains</fr:link>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(r_{n+2})=(a,b)]]></fr:tex> which implies the result.</fr:p><html:span
